    "question_id" : 52112639,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p><code>Object</code> might not be a direct parent, but it's always a super parent.</p>\n\n<pre><code>Child extends Parent\nParent extends Object\n\n |\n V\n\nChild [indirectly] extends Object\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 4775076,
      "reputation" : 143,
      "user_id" : 3858508,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/UJUon.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "admoca60",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3858508/admoca60"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1535709072,
    "creation_date" : 1535709072,
    "answer_id" : 52112834,
    "question_id" : 52112639,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>The right answer is Option 2. Any Java class inherit all parents for their parents. In other words.</p>\n\n<p>Class A extends Class B\nClass B extends Class C\nClass C extends Class D</p>\n\n<p>Class X extends A -> it means that A inherit all protected/package/public fields from B,C and D.</p>\n\n<p>In your example, Class Child inherit Parent properties but also Object properties in transitive mode.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 6591531,
        "reputation" : 3314,
        "user_id" : 6486187,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://graph.facebook.com/722616891201339/picture?type=large",
        "display_name" : "Abhishek Keshri",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/6486187/abhishek-keshri"
      },
      "edited" : false,
