    "last_activity_date" : 1535709760,
    "last_edit_date" : 1535709760,
    "creation_date" : 1535709075,
    "answer_id" : 52112835,
    "question_id" : 52112639,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Well it is an interesting discussion. I think it will be option no 2. As if you try the below code .</p>\n\n<pre><code>public static void main(String []args){\n      Parent p=new Parent();\n      Class c= p.getClass();\n\n      Child child =new Child();\n      Class c1= child.getClass();\n      System.out.println(c.getSuperclass());\n      System.out.println(c1.getSuperclass());\n\n }\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>You will get output as :</p>\n\n<pre><code>class java.lang.Object \nclass Parent\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 3381296,
      "reputation" : 5223,
      "user_id" : 2838289,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e70c153cab598a9e223988513532732f?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "LuCio",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2838289/lucio"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 7,
    "last_activity_date" : 1763655400,
    "last_edit_date" : 1763655400,
    "creation_date" : 1535709177,
    "answer_id" : 52112868,
    "question_id" : 52112639,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>The <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/10/docs/api/java/lang/Object.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">JavaDoc</a> says:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Class <code>Object</code> is the root of the class hierarchy. ...</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>If a class does not extend any other class by declaring it using the keyword <code>extends</code> it extends though implicit from <code>Object</code>.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/IandI/subclasses.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">documentation</a> says:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>In the absence of any other explicit superclass, every class is\nimplicitly a subclass of Object.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>See the <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se10/html/jls-8.html#d5e12064\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Example 8.1.4-1</a> &quot;<em>Direct Superclasses and Subclasses</em>&quot; in <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se10/html/jls-8.html#jls-8.1.4\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">JLS, chapter 8.1.4</a></p>\n<p>It shows that a <code>class Point { int x, y; }</code> &quot;<em>is a direct subclass of Object</em>&quot;</p>\n<p>Moreover the documentation says:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Classes can be derived from classes that are derived from classes that\nare derived from classes, and so on, and ultimately derived from the\ntopmost class, <code>Object</code>. Such a class is said to be descended from all\nthe classes in the inheritance chain stretching back to <code>Object</code>.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The JLS states it short and formal:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The subclass relationship is the transitive closure of the direct\nsubclass relationship.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Thus class <code>Object</code> is the superclass of all classes.</p>\n<p>But the documentation also says:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Excepting <code>Object</code>, which has no superclass, every class has one and only one direct superclass (single\ninheritance).</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Going on with the example a <code>class ColoredPoint extends Point { int color; }</code> &quot;<em>is a direct subclass of class <code>Point</code>.</em>&quot;. By the transitive relationship it's a (non-direct) subclass of class <code>Object</code>.</p>\n<p>Summarizing:<br />\n<code>Object</code> is either the direct superclass or by transitive relationship the last superclass of any other class.</p>\n<p>Answering the questions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><em>Java does not support multiple inheritance</em>: It provides single inheritance in a transitive way. Every class extends directly only one superclass.</li>\n<li><em>How is the relationship</em>: The class <code>Parent</code> corresponds to the class <code>Point</code> and the class <code>Child</code> to the class <code>ColoredPoint</code> of the JLS example. Only <em>Option 2</em> shows this relation.</li>\n</ul>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1718670,
      "reputation" : 4899,
      "user_id" : 1575188,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/8XmsL.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "fantaghirocco",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1575188/fantaghirocco"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1535709236,
    "last_edit_date" : 1592644375,
    "creation_date" : 1535709236,
    "answer_id" : 52112887,
    "question_id" : 52112639,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>From <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/lang/Object.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><code>Class Object</code></a></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><code>public class Object</code><br/>\nClass Object is the root of the class hierarchy.<br>\nEvery class has Object as a superclass.<br/> All objects, including arrays, implement the methods of this class.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This means that every Java class has <code>Object</code> as root in the hierarchy, not necessarily as its immediate parent.</p>\n"
  }, {
